Part 7

The chair came with the office. The office itself was really just two rooms above a spare-parts godown, which the company had converted in a hurry because nothing better was available yet in this industrial city. 

The chair was made of brown leatherette, cracked deeply along both armrests where the stuffing was beginning to show. One wheel was permanently stuck, which made the whole chair list two degrees to the left if you weren't careful when standing up.

Vikram's manager here, a sharp young man named Suresh, had tried twice to get it replaced during his first month.

"Sir, we can easily order a proper executive leather chair from Hyderabad," Suresh said. "The company budget allows for it, and it will look much more professional for meetings."

"This one works," Vikram said, adjusting a folder on his desk.

"It is falling apart, sir."

"It hasn't fallen apart yet," Vikram replied.

Suresh gave up after the second attempt. He filed his boss under the general category of eccentric, wealthy men he didn't need to understand in order to work for.

---

Vikram sat in the listing chair the night the first major factory workers' wage dispute came to his desk. 

Eleven men had gone three months without pay because a regional distributor had defaulted on his payments, and the company's own cash was temporarily tied up in a land deal that still hadn't cleared. 

Vikram could have waited. Legally, under the terms of the contract, he had every ground to wait until the distributor was taken to court.

But he sat in the cracked chair until past midnight, going through the ledger numbers twice. By morning, he had found a way to release a partial emergency payment from a different reserve account, telling Suresh to arrange the bank drafts before the workers even arrived at the office to ask.

"That is not how the corporate process usually works, sir," Suresh said, holding the draft authorization.

"I know."

"The head office in Calcutta will ask questions about this transfer."

"Let them ask," Vikram said, looking at his desk.

He sat in the chair again three weeks later, the night a second factory's water-supply request needed approval. It was a project that would cost the company far more than the state government would ever reimburse. 

He approved it anyway. He knew the alternative was six hundred local families carrying water two kilometers by hand indefinitely while the paperwork moved slowly through government channels designed to take years.

---

"Why not just replace the thing?" Reddy asked one afternoon, visiting the site and eyeing the cracked leatherette with open disapproval. "It looks like something waiting to collapse under you."

"Because it doesn't let me forget," Vikram said.

"Forget what?"

Vikram didn't answer immediately. He ran one thumb along the cracked edge of the left armrest, the way another man might touch an old scar to check if it was still there.

"Every time I sit in something comfortable, Reddy, I start making comfortable decisions," Vikram said, looking up. "This chair reminds me every few minutes that it could give way. It keeps me honest about what is actually at stake when I sign these papers."

Reddy looked at him for a long moment, the way a man looks at someone he is revising an old, hard opinion about. He didn't say anything about the chair then. 

He would, eventually—but that conversation belonged to a different night, a different pot of tea, still some weeks away. For now, the brown chair held, listing its two degrees to the left, and Vikram kept signing what needed signing, one cracked-leather night at a time.

[End of Part 7]
